        "subject": "LU-6148 ldlm: Strided locking prototype",
        "message": "LU-6148 ldlm: Strided locking prototype\n\nThis is a prototype/proof of concept, not intended to land\nas is.  It is missing at least one major set of changes\nfor handling conflicting locks, and has a great deal of\ndebug code which is intended as development help rather\nthan intended to land.  This is intended to start\nconcept and design review, and if that goes well, it will\nbe cleaned up.\n\nThis adds a new LDLM layer feature, strided locking.\nStrided locking makes it possible to improve shared file IO\nperformance.  Currently, if more than one client tries to\nwrite to the portion of a file on a given OST (IE, >1\nclient per OST), the two clients have lock contention\nproblems, and are serialized, even if their writes are\nnon-overlapping.  The usual case for this is strided IO,\nwhere clients write alternating blocks.\n\nIf a group of clients commit want to do strided IO to a\nsingle file, they can use an ioctl to request strided\nlocking behavior.\n\nThe client provides the number of clients in the strided\nIO, and when that client does an IO request, the lock\ngranted is a periodic lock which is periodic in the\nnumber of clients.  Locks are granted only on stripe size\nsegments.\n\nIE, if there are two clients in the IO, a lock which\ncovers every 2nd block is issued to each client, starting\nfrom the block where the IO was done.\n\nThis allows multiple clients to write to the same file on\na particular OST without being serialized by lock\ncontention.\n\nDesign doc and other details forthcoming in LU-6148.\n\nTest-Parameters: fortestonly\nSigned-off-by: Patrick Farrell <paf@cray.com>\nChange-Id: Ia529ac7cb94b4fb8e3d81e6080c16787107b4df0\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
